Scaling is the ability to increase or decrease resources based on workload demand.

Vertical Scaling

Increasing the power of a single server.

Add more CPU, RAM, or storage
Simple but has hardware limits
Example: upgrading an EC2 instance size
Horizontal Scaling

Adding more servers or instances.

Distributes workload across multiple machines
Improves availability and fault tolerance
Common in cloud environments
Auto Scaling

Automatically adjusts resources based on traffic or usage.

Scales out during high demand
Scales in during low demand
Helps reduce costs and improve performance
Elasticity

The cloud’s ability to rapidly scale resources up or down as needed.

Resources match current demand
Prevents overprovisioning
Load Balancing

Distributes incoming traffic across multiple servers.

Prevents one server from overload
Improves reliability and availability
Serverless Scaling

In services like AWS Lambda, scaling happens automatically without managing servers. AWS creates more function instances as requests increase.

Key Idea
Vertical scaling = bigger server
Horizontal scaling = more servers
Auto scaling = automatic adjustment
Elasticity = flexible resource usage
Load balancing = traffic distribution
